.SH SIZE UNITS
\f[B]\(enmin\-size\f[R] and \f[B]\(enmax\-size\f[R] accept an optional
unit suffix: \f[B]k\f[R] (1024 bytes), \f[B]M\f[R] (megabytes),
\f[B]G\f[R] (gigabytes).
No suffix means bytes.
Examples: \f[B]500\f[R], \f[B]10k\f[R], \f[B]2M\f[R], \f[B]1G\f[R].
.SH DURATION UNITS
\f[B]\(ennewer\f[R] and \f[B]\(enolder\f[R] accept a number followed by
a unit: \f[B]s\f[R] (seconds), \f[B]m\f[R] (minutes), \f[B]h\f[R]
(hours), \f[B]d\f[R] (days), \f[B]w\f[R] (weeks).
Examples: \f[B]30m\f[R], \f[B]1h\f[R], \f[B]7d\f[R].
.SH WILDCARDS
On Windows, cmd.exe and PowerShell do not expand \f[B]*\f[R] and
\f[B]?\f[R] wildcards before starting programs, so \f[B]files\f[R]
expands them itself.
\f[B]files src*\f[R] works the same as in bash.
\f[B][\&...]\f[R] is matched literally (brackets are legal Windows
filename characters).
\f[B]**\f[R] is rejected with a usage error \(em use the tool\(cqs own
recursive options instead.
A pattern that matches nothing is passed through unchanged so the normal
\(lqnot found\(rq error follows.
In cmd, quoting a pattern (e.g.\ \f[I]\(lqsrc*\(rq\f[R]) suppresses
expansion.
On Linux and macOS the shell expands wildcards as usual and
\f[B]files\f[R] does nothing extra.
Option values for \f[B]\(englob\f[R] and \f[B]\(enregex\f[R] are never
expanded.
.SH EXIT CODES
.TP
\f[B]0\f[R]
Success.
.TP
\f[B]1\f[R]
Runtime error (permission denied, invalid path, or partial walk with one
or more unreadable directories).
.TP
\f[B]125\f[R]
Usage error (bad arguments).
.PP
When directories cannot be enumerated, each unreadable path is reported
on stderr and the process exits \f[B]1\f[R] with \f[B]exit_reason:
walk_error_partial\f[R] in the \f[B]\(enjson\f[R] envelope, plus a
populated \f[B]walk_errors[]\f[R] array.
.SH STRUCTURED OUTPUT
Both \f[B]\(enndjson\f[R] and \f[B]\(enjson\f[R] write to
\f[B]stdout\f[R] per suite convention.
.PP
\f[B]\(enndjson\f[R] emits one JSON object per matching entry with
fields \f[B]path\f[R] (relative or absolute per \f[B]\(enabsolute\f[R]),
\f[B]name\f[R], \f[B]type\f[R] (\f[B]file\f[R] | \f[B]directory\f[R] |
\f[B]symlink\f[R]), \f[B]size_bytes\f[R] (integer, or \f[B]null\f[R] for
directory entries), \f[B]modified\f[R] (ISO 8601, or \f[B]null\f[R] when
not populated), \f[B]depth\f[R] (integer; \f[B]0\f[R] = root), and
\f[B]is_text\f[R] (boolean, only present when \f[B]\(entext\f[R] or
\f[B]\(enbinary\f[R] is used).
.PP
\f[B]\(enjson\f[R] emits a single envelope after the walk:
\f[B]tool\f[R], \f[B]version\f[R], \f[B]exit_code\f[R],
\f[B]exit_reason\f[R], \f[B]count\f[R], \f[B]searched_roots\f[R],
\f[B]walk_errors\f[R] (array of \f[B]{path, reason}\f[R] for unreadable
paths; empty on success).
Pre\-walk error envelopes (\f[B]path_not_found\f[R],
\f[B]not_a_directory\f[R]) additionally carry \f[B]error\f[R]
(human\-readable detail) with empty \f[B]searched_roots\f[R] and
\f[B]walk_errors\f[R] arrays for shape parity.
.PP
The \f[B]exit_reason\f[R] values are: \f[B]success\f[R],
\f[B]walk_error_partial\f[R], \f[B]path_not_found\f[R],
\f[B]not_a_directory\f[R], \f[B]usage_error\f[R],
\f[B]runtime_error\f[R].
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
\f[B]NO_COLOR\f[R]
If set, disables coloured output (no\-color.org).
.SH EXAMPLES
.IP
.EX
files src \-\-ext cs

files . \-\-text \-\-type f

files . \-\-newer 1h \-\-type f

files . \-\-long \-\-ext cs

files . \-\-gitignore \-\-no\-hidden \-\-ext cs

files . \-\-glob \(aq*.log\(aq | wargs rm

files . \-\-ndjson | jq \(aq.name\(aq

files . \-\-min\-size 1k \-\-max\-size 10M

files . \-\-glob \(aq*.log\(aq \-\-print0 | xargs \-0 rm
.EE
